<br>
Wernher von Braun turned 50 on March 23, 1962. At the time, the German rocketeer was director of Marshall Space Flight Center (MSFC), NASA's lead facility for rocket development. He could look back on a career that included the first large liquid-propellant missile (the German V-2, first launched in 1942) and launching the first American Earth satellite ( Explorer 1, 1958 ). Since President Kennedy's May 1961 &quot;Moon Speech,&quot; Von Braun could look forward to lunar expeditions using his giant Saturn and Nova rockets. In the present paper, Von Braun's fellow German expatriate H. H. Koelle, MSFC Future Projects Office director, attempts to predict the cost of Earth-moon transportation up to 1980. Koelle considers seven methods of transporting cargo and crew from the Earth to the moon: <br>
<br>
Number 7 I found particularly interesting.<br>
<br>
Direct mode - reusable nuclear spaceship: Koelle calls this mode &quot;first-class transportation.&quot; A reusable Earth-launch vehicle - a Nova Jr. II variant with a reduced chemical propellant load - places a nuclear-propulsion transport vehicle with enough propellant for the Earth-moon trip into Earth orbit. The nuclear spaceship flies to the moon, lands, and refuels for the moon-Earth trip. Lunar surface mission accomplished, it lifts off from the moon and flies back to Earth. Near Earth, the nuclear rocket fires to reduce the level of deceleration the crew feels during atmosphere reentry to about 1.5 times the pull of Earth's gravity. The spaceship deploys a &quot;flex wing&quot; at a height of 10 kilometers and glides to a landing, or lands under nuclear rocket power. The nuclear spaceship is then refurbished and reused. Flight tests for this mode would begin at the start of 1977, with operational flights beginning in 1979. Koelle warns, however, that Mode 7 would &quot;require the production of huge amounts of liquid hydrogen on the Moon, which at this time does not appear feasible.&quot; <br>
<br>
Number 3 also utilises reactor rocket technology for a direct mode.<br>
