<br>
1.<br>
<br>
Earth-Orbital Rendezvous (EOR) mode: An expendable two-stage chemical rocket designated Nova Jr. I launches a liquid hydrogen/liquid oxygen- propellant Earth-orbit-departure rocket stage. Nova Jr. I has five 1.5-million-pound thrust engines in its first stage and four 200,000-pound-thrust engines in its second stage. A second Nova Jr. I launches a two-stage lunar landing vehicle. Stage and lander dock in Earth orbit, then the stage fires its single 200,000-pound-thrust engine to place the lander on course for the moon. The crew lands the lander on the moon. After completing their surface mission, they lift off in the lander's upper stage, fly back to Earth, and directly enter Earth's atmosphere. Flight tests for this mode would begin at the start of 1965, with operational flights spanning mid-1967 to mid-1968. Writes Koelle: &quot;This mode of operation is very close to the mission profile which will probably be employed for the first Apollo flight. . .&quot;<br>
<br>
2.<br>
<br>
Direct mode - high-energy lander upper stage: Same as Mode 1, except the lander upper stage uses &quot;high-energy&quot; chemical propellants, reducing total lander mass by one-third. This eliminates the need to separately launch the two-stage lunar lander and Earth-orbit-departure stage, permitting a single Nova Jr. I to launch the lunar expedition. Flight tests for this mode would begin at the start of 1965, with operational flights from the start of 1967 to mid-1969.<br>
<br>
3.<br>
<br>
Direct mode - nuclear Earth-orbit departure stage: Same as Mode 2, except the Earth-orbit-departure stage contains a nuclear reactor which is used to heat and expel liquid hydrogen propellant, and the lunar lander is a single-stage vehicle with high-performance chemical propellants. Flight tests would begin in mid-1967, with operational flights from mid-1969 to the end of 1972.<br>
<br>
4.<br>
<br>
EOR mode - reusable Earth-launch rocket: Uses a reusable Earth-launch rocket called Nova Jr. II with the same thrust capability as Nova Jr. I, along with a nuclear Earth-orbit-departure stage. Adding recovery systems - presumably parachutes and flotation devices - to the launch vehicle reduces the weight it can place in Earth orbit; therefore, two Nova Jr. II's and one rendezvous in Earth orbit are required for each lunar expedition in this mode. Flight testing would start at the beginning of 1969, and operational flights would start at the beginning of 1971.<br>
<br>
5.<br>
<br>
Lunar-Orbit Refueling mode might best be applied to an early lunar base. A reusable nuclear ferry provides cargo and crew transport between Earth orbit and lunar orbit. This eliminates the &quot;hazardous&quot; direct reentry of earlier modes. The ferry is refueled in Earth orbit between round-trip flights. The reusable single-stage lunar lander provides transport from the ferry in lunar orbit to the lunar surface, with the ferry refueling the lander. Flight testing starts at the beginning of 1970, with operational flights spanning 1972-76.<br>
<br>
6.<br>
<br>
Lunar-Surface Refueling mode is similar to Mode 5. Koelle calls this &quot;of interest only if it becomes possible to produce propellants on the Moon.&quot; Availability of lunar propellants means that the nuclear-propelled ferry need not carry lander propellants. This means that it can carry more cargo; the lunar lander thus doubles in size to carry the extra cargo and needs a more powerful engine. Flight testing for this mode begins at the start of 1973, with operational flights spanning 1975-78.<br>
<br>
7.<br>
<br>
Direct mode - reusable nuclear spaceship: Koelle calls this mode &quot;first-class transportation.&quot; A reusable Earth-launch vehicle - a Nova Jr. II variant with a reduced chemical propellant load - places a nuclear-propulsion transport vehicle with enough propellant for the Earth-moon trip into Earth orbit. The nuclear spaceship flies to the moon, lands, and refuels for the moon-Earth trip. Lunar surface mission accomplished, it lifts off from the moon and flies back to Earth. Near Earth, the nuclear rocket fires to reduce the level of deceleration the crew feels during atmosphere reentry to about 1.5 times the pull of Earth's gravity. The spaceship deploys a &quot;flex wing&quot; at a height of 10 kilometers and glides to a landing, or lands under nuclear rocket power. The nuclear spaceship is then refurbished and reused. Flight tests for this mode would begin at the start of 1977, with operational flights beginning in 1979. Koelle warns, however, that Mode 7 would &quot;require the production of huge amounts of liquid hydrogen on the Moon, which at this time does not appear feasible.&quot; <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Koelle estimates that the round-trip cost per astronaut for Mode 1 will be about $40 million. He recommends that this mode be used for as short a time as possible. Mode 2 will slash cost per astronaut to $20 million; Mode 3 will cut this further, to $10 million (&quot;the best that can be expected with expendable systems,&quot; writes Koelle). Reusable vehicles (Mode 5) cut costs to $2 million per astronaut. Producing propellants on the moon reduces round-trip cost per astronaut to about $700,000. Koelle then outlines an ambitious lunar transportation model in which cost per pound delivered to the lunar surface falls from $1600/pound in 1967 to $300/pound in 1976. The year 1967 (Mode 1) sees six successful Earth-moon round-trips with 342,000 pounds of cargo delivered to the lunar surface, for a cost of $790 million. The year 1970 (Mode 3) sees 19 Earth-moon round-trips with 674,000 pounds of cargo delivered to the lunar surface, at a cost of $875 million, and 1972 (Mode 5) sees 22 Earth-moon round-trips with 778,000 pounds of cargo on the moon, at a cost of $937 million. In 1978, the peak year in Koelle's model, 112 Mode 6-type flights deliver 13,380,000 pounds of cargo to the moon for $1.155 billion.<br>
